Bounty Hacker

Target IP: 10.10.149.100
Challenge Description: You were boasting on and on about your elite hacker skills in the bar and a few Bounty Hunters decided they'd take you up on claims! Prove your status is more than just a few glasses at the bar. I sense bell peppers & beef in your future!

Reconnaissance


I performed a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.149.100 -p- and obtained the result shown above. By the looks of it, there are three TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, and HTTP on their standard ports. I will now perform an aggressive scan against these open ports to identify its applications.


I performed an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.149.100 -p 21,22,80 and obtained the result shown above. Again, there are three TCP ports open. The FTP application running on port 21 is interesting, as it allows anonymous login. There is also SSH application on port 22, but I do not have any credentials. The target machine is also running a web server on port 80. I will firstly enumerate the FTP application on port 21.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

I connected to the FTP application on the target machine by running the command ftp 10.10.149.100. When trying to obtain the directory listing, there would be a timeout. To overcome this, I ran the command passiv. Then running the command ls -la shows there are two accessible files: locks.txt and task.txt. I used the get command to download both text files on my machine, as shown above.


Running the command cat locks.txt returns the result shown above. This file seems to contain a list of possible passwords?


The file task.txt contains the information shown above. The username lin sounds interesting to me. It also mentions to protect vicious -- is this a possible username too? Time to enumerate the web server on port 80 now.

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. There are multiple usernames like spike, jet, ed, and faye. I viewed the source-code of the webpage but I did not find anything useful. I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.149.100/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x html,php,txt and did not find anything useful either.

Exploitation


I created a file with the name usernames.txt that contains the entries shown above. This file contains the possible usernames I found from enumeration. Now I have two possible attack vectors using the usernames.txt and lock.txt files: bruteforce the FTP, otherwise bruteforce the SSH. However, the second option more viable.


I ran the command hydra -L usernames.txt -P locks.txt 10.10.149.100 ssh to bruteforce the SSH application and got a hit, as shown above. The application hydra managed to bruteforce the password RedDr4gonSynd1cat3 of the user lin. Now I can SSH into the target machine using the new bruteforce credentials.


I SSHed into the target machine using the command ssh lin@10.10.149.100 and the password RedDr4gonSynd1cat3. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user lin, as shown above. Time to enumerate further to escalate my privileges on the target machine to root.

Privilege Escalation


Since I have the password of the user lin, I ran the command sudo -l and obtained the information shown above. This user can run the binary /bin/tar with root privileges. Therefore, obtaining a root shell on the target machine is super simple.


To obtain a root shell on the target machine, I executed the command sudo tar -cf /dev/null /dev/null --checkpoint=1 --checkpoint-action=exec=/bin/sh. Now I have a root shell as shown above. GG :)
